arch:property.oc:show_val: This coarse, compacted Strong Brown (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/6) layer is a thick, dense stratum of fill and collapse characteristically found in the upper levels of deposit throughout the temple precinct. While small inclusions such as pottery, metal, bone, stone and charcoal are present throughout the fill, the primary finds are large architectural fragments fallen down from the upper levels of the temple structure. Large fragments such as arch stones, roof stones, stair treads, and doorjambs are particularly prolific. Large amounts of molded stucco decoration, presumably from the north face of the south wall, were also found in this locus.
Extends up to north faces of Loci 2, 3, 4 and 17, and south faces of Loci 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.
Closing Levels: Sub datum 85C – 3.42 m, 907.804 m (northwest), 907.488 m (northeast), 907.178 m (southeast).
Opening Levels: Sub datum 85C -.25 m, 910.494 m (northwest), 910.418 m (northeast), 909.878 m (southeast).
Phase XI: Further collapse post CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. The east Porch columns and Central Arch collapse and fluvial deposits continue to accumulate.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Locus 1 extends the full length and width of Trench 85.
Massive collapses continue and overburden accumulates in the South Corridor containing a vast number of architectural elements.
